Here is the full technical breakdown of Dennis's simulation, dissecting the variables, the mathematical engine, and what the results actually proved for the journal.
1. Model Definitions & Variables (The RCFT Ontology)
This section of the code sets up the physical laws and boundaries of the minimal toy universe.
•	states ($U$): The 8 hidden, deterministic upstream relational nodes ($u_1$ through $u_8$, coded as 0 to 7).
•	proj ($\Pi$): The lossy projection map. It forces the 8 hidden states into 4 observable "bins" ($A, B, C, D$). This many-to-one mapping ($\Pi(u_i) \to O$) is the exact source of the apparent quantum stochasticity.
•	neighbors ($N(u_i)$): The geometric topology. It defines the rigid, deterministic graph of which hidden states connect to which.
The Physics Constants:
•	alpha ($\alpha = 1.0$): The weight of spatial locality. It penalizes moving across the graph.
•	beta ($\beta = 2.0$): The weight of observable stability. It heavily penalizes transitions that force the 3D shadow to jump to a new observable bin.
•	lam ($\lambda = 0.0 \to 1.0$): The Topological Ratchet / History Drag. When zero, the universe has no memory. When above zero, the universe learns and creates attractors.
•	T ($T = 1.0$): Admissibility Tolerance. The strictness of the universe. A lower $T$ forces the system to strictly obey the friction gradients; a higher $T$ allows the particle to wander chaotically despite high friction.
•	tau ($\tau = 5.0$): The memory scaling parameter. It dictates how quickly a repeatedly traveled path hits its maximum friction discount.
•	mem_window ($50$): The physical limit of the universe's memory. It only tracks the last 50 topological transitions, allowing old, abandoned pathways to "heal" and return to high friction.
•	trans_counts ($n_{ij}$): A dynamic matrix tracking exactly how many times the transition $u_i \to u_j$ was taken within the memory window.
2. The Mathematical Equations (The Causal Engine)
Dennis translated the three philosophical pillars of RCFT into strict, computable mathematics.
Equation 1: The Friction Functional ($F$)
$$F_t(u_i \to u_j) = \alpha \cdot d_{\text{graph}} + \beta \cdot \Delta_{\text{proj}} + \lambda \cdot M_t(u_i \to u_j)$$
This calculates the relational tension of a potential jump.
•	$d_{\text{graph}}$ evaluates if the jump is valid on the network.
•	$\Delta_{\text{proj}}$ adds the $\beta$ penalty only if the jump changes the observable state.
•	The Memory Term ($M_t$):
$$M_t = -\left(1 - e^{-n_{ij} / \tau}\right)$$
Notice the negative sign. Because $n_{ij}$ (times traveled) is positive, this term outputs a negative number. This means $\lambda M_t$ subtracts from the total friction. The more a path is used, the cheaper it becomes to use it again.
Equation 2: Admissibility Transition Probability ($P$)
$$P(u_i \to u_j) = \frac{e^{-F_t(u_i \to u_j) / T}}{Z}$$
(Where $Z$ is the sum of all available pathway weights).
This is a Boltzmann-like softmax function. The universe evaluates the friction of all adjacent nodes and probabilistically selects the path of least resistance.
Equation 3: Empirical Coherence ($C$)
$$C(t) = -\frac{1}{t} \sum_{s=1}^{t} F_s$$
This serves as the diagnostic Lyapunov indicator. It is the rolling average of the negative friction over time, showing the system globally trending toward stability.
